<article class="blog-post">
  <div class="post-header">
    <span class="post-title">&#9876;&#65039; Last Man Standing Mindset</span>
    <span class="post-date">May 24th 2026</span>
  </div>
  <div class="post-body">
    <p>
      The last man standing mindset is betting on endurance over fireworks. Most
      races are not won by the fastest runner, but by the one still moving when
      everyone else sat down, the way the tortoise beat the hare by refusing to
      stop. Intensity burns bright and burns out; consistency compounds.
    </p>
    <hr class="post-divider" />
    <p>
      <strong>&#128214; Example:</strong> in <em>The Psychology of Money</em>,
      Morgan Housel argues that survival beats brilliance. The people who come
      out ahead are rarely the ones with the best single run, but the ones who
      never got knocked out, so time could quietly do the heavy lifting.
      Avoiding ruin matters more than chasing the spectacular.
    </p>
    <blockquote class="book-quote">
      <p>"But you need short-term paranoia to keep you alive long enough to exploit long-term optimism."</p>
      <cite>Morgan Housel, The Psychology of Money</cite>
    </blockquote>
  </div>
